"{\"uid\": \"news.sky.com-story-moulin-rouge-windmill-restored-after-collapse-in-time-for-olympics-13174066\", \"text\": \"The cabaret - which is marking its 135th anniversary this year - scrambled to repair the damage before the Olympic torch relay passes through the area on 15 July.  News reporter@niamhielynch  Saturday 6 July 2024 11:43, UK  Paris' famed Moulin Rouge cabaret got its iconic red windmill back on Friday after it collapsed earlier this year.  A special ceremony that featured can-can dancing on the plaza outside marked the restoration of the windmill - an emblem of the surrounding Montmartre neighbourhood.  The mill's huge sails and part of the cabaret's illuminated signcrashed to the groundafter a show in April due to a technical problem, according to its director.  Please use Chrome browser for a more accessible video player    No one was hurt and the mayor of Paris' 18th district said the structure was not in danger.  The cabaret scrambled to repair the damage before the Olympic torch relay passes through the area on 15 July.  The windmill was first illuminated on 6 October 1889 at the opening of the Moulin Rouge. The cabaret is best known as the birthplace of the modern form of the can-can dance.  The cabaret, which is marking its 135th anniversary this year, is a major tourist attraction and was the subject of the 2001Baz Luhrmannfilm musical starringNicole Kidman.  Jordan Bardella: Meet the man who could become France's next president  France reveals new national military service amid fears of Russian threat  France's Emmanuel Macron unveils new military service to combat Russia threat  Read more:Tate allowed to leave RomaniaArchbishop brands Pope 'servant of Satan'French politicians attacked on election campaign trail  Keep up with all the latest news from the UK and around the world by following Sky News  A musical version of the film also debuted on Broadway in 2019 and opened on the West End in 2022.  More than 600,000 people visit the cabaret every year.  Be the first to getBreaking News  Install the Sky News app for free  \"}"